solarbody.name: Sun
solarbody.description: The Sun is the star at the center of the Solar System.

solarbody.name: Mercury
solarbody.description: Mercury is the smallest and closest to the Sun of the eight planets in the Solar System, with an orbital period of about 88 Earth days.

solarbody.name: Venus
solarbody.description: Venus is the second planet from the Sun, orbiting it every 224.7 Earth days. It has no natural satellite. It is named after the Roman goddess of love and beauty.

solarbody.name: Earth
solarbody.description: Earth, also known as "the Earth" and "the World" and sometimes referred to as the "Blue Planet", the "Blue Marble", Terra or "Gaia", is the third-most distant planet from the Sun, the densest planet in the Solar System and the only celestial body known to accommodate life.

solarbody.name: Mars
solarbody.description: Mars is the fourth planet from the Sun and the second smallest planet in the Solar System, after Mercury.

solarbody.name: Jupiter
solarbody.description: Jupiter is the fifth planet from the Sun and the largest planet in the Solar System. It is a gas giant with mass one-thousandth of that of the Sun but is two and a half times the mass of all the other planets in the Solar System combined.

solarbody.name: Saturn
solarbody.description: Saturn is the sixth planet from the Sun and the second largest planet in the Solar System, after Jupiter. Named after the Roman god of agriculture, its astronomical symbol represents the god's sickle.

solarbody.name: Uranus
solarbody.description: Uranus is the seventh planet from the Sun. It has the third-largest planetary radius and fourth-largest planetary mass in the Solar System.

solarbody.name: Neptune
solarbody.description: Neptune is the eighth and farthest planet from the Sun in the Solar System. It is the fourth-largest planet by diameter and the third-largest by mass. Among the gaseous planets in the solar system, Neptune is the most dense.
